tal iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor serpentinization, alkaline vent conditions, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Serpentinization of ultramafic rocks produces H2; coupled CO2 reduction on Fe-bearing minerals yields reduced one-carbon compounds including formaldehyde precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal serpentinization is a robust source of H2 and reduced carbon feedstock in alkaline vents, providing the geochemical reducing power needed for subsequent keto-acid and aldehyde synthesis. The report identifies serpentinization as central to vent H2 supply and reduced carbon chemistry, with magnetite and Fe phases involved in CO2 hydrogenation (McCollom and Seewald, 2007; Sleep et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to formic acid on iron-sulfur minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4), mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated hydrogenation of CO2 on Fe-S minerals produces formate/formic acid as a low-barrier reductant and carbon carrier.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite and related Fe-S minerals are repeatedly implicated in prebiotic CO2 reduction and in iron-sulfur-world style carbon fixation. The report further notes that formic acid lowers barriers for hydration and amination steps relevant to amino-acid precursor chemistry, making it a useful connected intermediate (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical generation of HCN in volcanic surface settings\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, volcanic plume or evaporitic pool input, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-photochemical and volcanic discharge-like chemistry converts reduced C/N feedstock into HCN, which accumulates in surface waters and aerosols.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report identifies HCN as the central feedstock of valine formation in both Strecker and cyanosulfidic systems and highlights its rapid production in lightning-rich volcanic settings. TiO2-mediated photochemistry is included as the required mineral-supported surface photochemical analog (Miller, 1953; Parker et al., 2011; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-type generation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde stabilization\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed subaerial geothermal field or evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Borate-stabilized carbonyl chemistry and photochemical processing convert formaldehyde into glycolaldehyde, a key C2 carbonyl intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde as important shared intermediates across cyanosulfidic and sugar-forming networks, and borate minerals as stabilizers of reactive sugars and carbonyl pools. This reaction connects reduced hydrothermal one-carbon feedstock to surface C-C bond forming chemistry (Ritson and Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation to branched aldehyde precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals, phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, neutral pH buffered by phosphate, cyanosulfidic regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iterative HCN-derived homologation and reduction under UV/H2S conditions produces longer and branched carbon skeletons, converging on isobutyraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research findings explicitly state that in the Sutherland-Patel cyanosulfidic network valine arises through reductive homologation of HCN and derivatives, with 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile as a precursor and isobutyraldehyde as an experimentally relevant branched aldehyde precursor. Phosphate-buffered, UV-driven HCN/H2S chemistry is therefore used here (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol addition of isobutyraldehyde with formaldehyde to hydroxypivaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals, borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH aqueous solution; water-compatible aldol chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Neutral-pH aldol condensation couples isobutyraldehyde and formaldehyde to form hydroxypivaldehyde in water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically highlights Powner-group work showing selective aldol reaction of isobutyraldehyde with formaldehyde to hydroxypivaldehyde under neutral aqueous conditions, linking valine precursors to pantetheine/CoA chemistry. This node is included to capture the documented systems-chemistry role of the branched aldehyde pool (Liu et al., 2019; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of valine nitrile from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker conditions in evaporitic pool or volcanic pond, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical literature-supported atmospheric/surface route to valine described in the report: isobutyraldehyde plus NH3 and HCN yields valine nitrile. Montmorillonite is included as a concentrating and scaffolding mineral and phosphate as a buffer/mineral support in surface settings (Miller, 1953; Bada, 2013; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine nitrile to valinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous hydrolysis; formic acid-assisted hydration lowers barrier\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile undergoes hydration to the amide, aided by acidic/formic acid microenvironments.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly states that Strecker conversion proceeds through valine amide before valine, and also notes computational evidence that formic acid substantially lowers nitrile hydration barriers. This makes valinamide a justified intermediate in a connected prebiotic sequence (Danger et al., 2012; Bouchard et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valinamide to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"continued aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amide hydrolysis furnishes the alpha-amino acid valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the second hydrolytic step of the classic Strecker route described in the report, converting valine amide to valine in aqueous prebiotic settings (Miller, 1953; Bada, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive carboxylation to alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4), pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, Fe-S mineral surfaces, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe-S surfaces mediate reductive carboxylation/oxidation of branched C4 carbonyl feedstock to the corresponding C5 alpha-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report emphasizes that greigite and pyrrhotite catalyze reductive carboxylation chemistry related to pyruvate formation and that analogous reactions with larger substrates are hypothesized to yield the C5 keto acids required for valine synthesis. This step is therefore included as a literature-grounded but still partly speculative connector between branched aldehydes and alpha-ketoisovalerate in vent chemistry (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"5 bar H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni0 with greigite (Fe3S4) mineral support\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-11, optimum near pH 11, 72 h, serpentinizing vent analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoisovalerate undergoes reductive amination with ammonia under H2 on Ni/Fe-S catalytic surfaces to form valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest direct literature route to valine in the report. Kaur and co-workers showed that nickel nanoparticles catalyze reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine at about 80 degrees C, pH 11, and 5 bar H2 with yields up to about 50%, while the broader hydrothermal context implicates greigite and related iron-sulfur minerals as plausible vent catalysts and supports. The exact vent-like conditions are preserved here (Kaur et al., 2021; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Primitive transamination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"333-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyridoxamine-like cofactor with dissolved metal ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool or mineral interface; Cu2+ or Zn2+ trace ions plausible\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Abiotic transamination of alpha-ketoisovalerate by amino donor pools regenerates and amplifies valine in proto-metabolic exchange.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that pyridoxamine, an abiotic vitamin B6 analog, catalyzes transamination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids including valine in the presence of metal ions, linking geochemistry to protometabolic continuity. This reaction is represented as an amplification/recycling step rather than a net source from a separate amino donor node to keep the graph compact and connected (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry or mineral-mediated peptide coupling of valine to valylvaline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral interface or manganese oxide surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling or low-water activity; peptide formation favored over extended times\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of valine monomers under mineral-assisted dehydration yields a simple dipeptide reservoir.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report notes that manganese oxides efficiently catalyze amino-acid polymerization and that the same principles should extend to valine despite steric hindrance. Inclusion of valylvaline shows how surface- or geothermal-generated valine feeds forward into protobiological assembly (Rode et al., 1999; Rahman et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Peptide hydrolysis recycling valylvaline to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reversible pool chemistry, hydration during wet phases\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the dipeptide recycles free valine back into the monomer pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This recycling step is included to maintain connectivity between peptide assembly and monomer supply in fluctuating prebiotic environments and reflects the reversible nature of peptide condensation/hydrolysis under wet-dry or geothermal cycles discussed in systems chemistry treatments (Forsythe et al., 2015; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Classic Strecker from volcanic HCN and cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface-generated HCN and branched aldehyde converge in a canonical Strecker sequence followed by two-step hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feed into surface branched Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon produces formaldehyde, which feeds surface cyanosulfidic homologation to isobutyraldehyde and then Strecker valine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formic-acid-assisted Strecker hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formic acid lowers nitrile hydration barriers, supporting conversion of valine nitrile through valinamide to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Powner-linked aldehyde network to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde participates in neutral aqueous aldol chemistry to hydroxypivaldehyde, illustrating its persistence in a compatible cofactor-producing network before re-entering Strecker valine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent chemistry forms alpha-ketoisovalerate from reduced carbon and branched carbonyl precursors and directly aminates it to valine under Ni/H2/alkaline conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate-supported keto acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction to formic acid and Fe-S carboxylation chemistry support assembly of alpha-ketoisovalerate, followed by direct reductive amination to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-to-vent transfer via isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"A branched aldehyde synthesized in cyanosulfidic surface pools is transported to hydrothermal settings, where Fe-S/Ni catalysis converts it to alpha-ketoisovalerate and then valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal valine followed by primitive transamination amplification\",\n      \"description\": \"Once valine is produced hydrothermally, alpha-ketoisovalerate/valine transamination cycles maintain and amplify valine within proto-metabolic pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker valine feeding peptide assembly\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface-synthesized valine enters biochemical assembly as valylvaline, demonstrating onward incorporation into primitive peptides while remaining chemically recyclable.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Peptide recycling route replenishing valine pool\",\n      \"description\": \"Valine incorporated into primitive peptides is released again by hydrolysis, creating a dynamic monomer-polymer cycle linked to both surface and hydrothermal production routes.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets valine through an integrated prebiotic system centered on four literature-supported hubs: hydrogen cyanide, formaldehyde, isobutyraldehyde, and alpha-ketoisovalerate. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon and alpha-keto acids through serpentinization-driven H2, CO2 reduction, and iron-sulfur/Ni-mediated carboxylation-amination sequences. Surface chemistry supplies branched aldehydes and aminonitriles through Strecker and cyanosulfidic routes using HCN, H2S, UV, phosphate buffering, sulfide minerals, borate-stabilized carbonyl chemistry, and TiO2 photochemistry. Biochemical/prebiotic stages convert convergent intermediates into valine by hydrolysis, transamination, and peptide incorporation. Ten distinct pathways are represented as different valid routes through the same connected bipartite graph, with multiple convergences at isobutyraldehyde, valine nitrile, and alpha-ketoisovalerate.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H10O2", "iupac_name": "3-hydroxy-2,2-dimethylpropanal", "common_name": "hydroxypivaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O2/c1-5(2,3-6)4-7/h3,7H,4H2,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine nitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H11NO", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanamide", "common_name": "valinamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H2,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovaleric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C10H20N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valylvaline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H20N2O3/c1-5(2)7(9(13)14)11-8(6(3)4)10(15)12/h5-8H,11H2,1-4H3,(H,12,15)(H,13,14)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Serpentinization-driven generation of hydrogen and reduced carbon feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_002", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor serpentinization, alkaline vent conditions, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Serpentinization of ultramafic rocks produces H2; coupled CO2 reduction on Fe-bearing minerals yields reduced one-carbon compounds including formaldehyde precursors.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal serpentinization is a robust source of H2 and reduced carbon feedstock in alkaline vents, providing the geochemical reducing power needed for subsequent keto-acid and aldehyde synthesis. The report identifies serpentinization as central to vent H2 supply and reduced carbon chemistry, with magnetite and Fe phases involved in CO2 hydrogenation (McCollom and Seewald, 2007; Sleep et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "CO2 reduction to formic acid on iron-sulfur minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4), mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated hydrogenation of CO2 on Fe-S minerals produces formate/formic acid as a low-barrier reductant and carbon carrier.", "reasoning": "Greigite and related Fe-S minerals are repeatedly implicated in prebiotic CO2 reduction and in iron-sulfur-world style carbon fixation. The report further notes that formic acid lowers barriers for hydration and amination steps relevant to amino-acid precursor chemistry, making it a useful connected intermediate (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Photochemical generation of HCN in volcanic surface settings", "inputs": ["mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, volcanic plume or evaporitic pool input, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "UV-photochemical and volcanic discharge-like chemistry converts reduced C/N feedstock into HCN, which accumulates in surface waters and aerosols.", "reasoning": "The research report identifies HCN as the central feedstock of valine formation in both Strecker and cyanosulfidic systems and highlights its rapid production in lightning-rich volcanic settings. TiO2-mediated photochemistry is included as the required mineral-supported surface photochemical analog (Miller, 1953; Parker et al., 2011; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formose-type generation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde stabilization", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals, TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed subaerial geothermal field or evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Borate-stabilized carbonyl chemistry and photochemical processing convert formaldehyde into glycolaldehyde, a key C2 carbonyl intermediate.", "reasoning": "The report identifies glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde as important shared intermediates across cyanosulfidic and sugar-forming networks, and borate minerals as stabilizers of reactive sugars and carbonyl pools. This reaction connects reduced hydrothermal one-carbon feedstock to surface C-C bond forming chemistry (Ritson and Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation to branched aldehyde precursor", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals, phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, neutral pH buffered by phosphate, cyanosulfidic regime"}, "mechanism": "Iterative HCN-derived homologation and reduction under UV/H2S conditions produces longer and branched carbon skeletons, converging on isobutyraldehyde.", "reasoning": "The deep research findings explicitly state that in the Sutherland-Patel cyanosulfidic network valine arises through reductive homologation of HCN and derivatives, with 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile as a precursor and isobutyraldehyde as an experimentally relevant branched aldehyde precursor. Phosphate-buffered, UV-driven HCN/H2S chemistry is therefore used here (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Aldol addition of isobutyraldehyde with formaldehyde to hydroxypivaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals, borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH aqueous solution; water-compatible aldol chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Neutral-pH aldol condensation couples isobutyraldehyde and formaldehyde to form hydroxypivaldehyde in water.", "reasoning": "The report specifically highlights Powner-group work showing selective aldol reaction of isobutyraldehyde with formaldehyde to hydroxypivaldehyde under neutral aqueous conditions, linking valine precursors to pantetheine/CoA chemistry. This node is included to capture the documented systems-chemistry role of the branched aldehyde pool (Liu et al., 2019; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Strecker synthesis of valine nitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous Strecker conditions in evaporitic pool or volcanic pond, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical literature-supported atmospheric/surface route to valine described in the report: isobutyraldehyde plus NH3 and HCN yields valine nitrile. Montmorillonite is included as a concentrating and scaffolding mineral and phosphate as a buffer/mineral support in surface settings (Miller, 1953; Bada, 2013; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine nitrile to valinamide", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis; formic acid-assisted hydration lowers barrier"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile undergoes hydration to the amide, aided by acidic/formic acid microenvironments.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly states that Strecker conversion proceeds through valine amide before valine, and also notes computational evidence that formic acid substantially lowers nitrile hydration barriers. This makes valinamide a justified intermediate in a connected prebiotic sequence (Danger et al., 2012; Bouchard et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of valinamide to valine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "continued aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Amide hydrolysis furnishes the alpha-amino acid valine.", "reasoning": "This is the second hydrolytic step of the classic Strecker route described in the report, converting valine amide to valine in aqueous prebiotic settings (Miller, 1953; Bada, 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive carboxylation to alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4), pyrite (FeS2)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, Fe-S mineral surfaces, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Fe-S surfaces mediate reductive carboxylation/oxidation of branched C4 carbonyl feedstock to the corresponding C5 alpha-keto acid.", "reasoning": "The report emphasizes that greigite and pyrrhotite catalyze reductive carboxylation chemistry related to pyruvate formation and that analogous reactions with larger substrates are hypothesized to yield the C5 keto acids required for valine synthesis. This step is therefore included as a literature-grounded but still partly speculative connector between branched aldehydes and alpha-ketoisovalerate in vent chemistry (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353-373K", "pressure": "5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni0 with greigite (Fe3S4) mineral support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-11, optimum near pH 11, 72 h, serpentinizing vent analog"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoisovalerate undergoes reductive amination with ammonia under H2 on Ni/Fe-S catalytic surfaces to form valine.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest direct literature route to valine in the report. Kaur and co-workers showed that nickel nanoparticles catalyze reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine at about 80 degrees C, pH 11, and 5 bar H2 with yields up to about 50%, while the broader hydrothermal context implicates greigite and related iron-sulfur minerals as plausible vent catalysts and supports. The exact vent-like conditions are preserved here (Kaur et al., 2021; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Primitive transamination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "333-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pyridoxamine-like cofactor with dissolved metal ions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool or mineral interface; Cu2+ or Zn2+ trace ions plausible"}, "mechanism": "Abiotic transamination of alpha-ketoisovalerate by amino donor pools regenerates and amplifies valine in proto-metabolic exchange.", "reasoning": "The report states that pyridoxamine, an abiotic vitamin B6 analog, catalyzes transamination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids including valine in the presence of metal ions, linking geochemistry to protometabolic continuity. This reaction is represented as an amplification/recycling step rather than a net source from a separate amino donor node to keep the graph compact and connected (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Wet-dry or mineral-mediated peptide coupling of valine to valylvaline", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "363K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral interface or manganese oxide surface", "aqueous": "false", "other": "geothermal cycling or low-water activity; peptide formation favored over extended times"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of valine monomers under mineral-assisted dehydration yields a simple dipeptide reservoir.", "reasoning": "The report notes that manganese oxides efficiently catalyze amino-acid polymerization and that the same principles should extend to valine despite steric hindrance. Inclusion of valylvaline shows how surface- or geothermal-generated valine feeds forward into protobiological assembly (Rode et al., 1999; Rahman et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Peptide hydrolysis recycling valylvaline to valine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "reversible pool chemistry, hydration during wet phases"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis of the dipeptide recycles free valine back into the monomer pool.", "reasoning": "This recycling step is included to maintain connectivity between peptide assembly and monomer supply in fluctuating prebiotic environments and reflects the reversible nature of peptide condensation/hydrolysis under wet-dry or geothermal cycles discussed in systems chemistry treatments (Forsythe et al., 2015; Muchowska, Varma and Moran, 2020)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classic Strecker from volcanic HCN and cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde", "description": "Surface-generated HCN and branched aldehyde converge in a canonical Strecker sequence followed by two-step hydrolysis to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde feed into surface branched Strecker route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbon produces formaldehyde, which feeds surface cyanosulfidic homologation to isobutyraldehyde and then Strecker valine synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001",