  \"Avoid self-referential product loops unless modeling catalysis separately from stoichiometric transformation\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.62\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.69,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.96,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is a sensible extension of the Strecker route into primitive peptide chemistry. The peptide-formation step is plausible under wet-dry or mineral-mediated conditions, but the network gives no manganese oxide support despite the literature emphasizing Mn oxides for peptide assembly. The core valine branch remains stronger than the polymerization add-on.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Support peptide coupling with Mn oxide or activated nitrile chemistry consistent with the literature\",\n        \"Clarify whether peptide formation occurs in dry-down cycles, mineral surfaces, or condensation-promoting media\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.87\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.97,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"The recycling logic is chemically sensible because peptide hydrolysis can replenish free valine. This route forms a coherent pool-maintenance story, but it still depends on the same weak HCN and branched aldehyde origin steps. As with P9, peptide chemistry is plausible but under-specified relative to the literature.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use literature-backed peptide assembly catalysts or environmental cycling details\",\n        \"Treat peptide recycling as a secondary module rather than evidence for primary target synthesis strength\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically strong and clearly designed as a connected bipartite graph with multiple hubs, convergences, and cross-environment flow. It successfully reaches valine through two major literature-recognizable motifs: a Strecker branch via isobutyraldehyde/valine nitrile/valinamide and a hydrothermal branch via alpha-ketoisovalerate reductive amination. The strongest feature is environmental interconnection: hydrothermal reduced-carbon feedstocks support surface aldehyde chemistry, and surface/hydrothermal products feed biochemical assembly and recycling. However, several reactions are too compressed or chemically weak relative to the provided literature. Most notably, HCN generation from only H2 and NH3 is poorly aligned with the volcanic/spark-discharge literature; the cyanosulfidic production of isobutyraldehyde is plausible in broad systems-chemistry terms but not explicitly justified at the level written; and the hydrothermal generation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from CO2, H2, and isobutyraldehyde is speculative. One reaction, the primitive transamination step, is not stoichiometrically valid. Literature alignment is mixed: the network captures the right named intermediates and major themes from Miller-Urey, Sutherland/Patel, Powner, and hydrothermal reductive amination studies, but it