ce is sound. However, the serpentinization step directly yielding formaldehyde from CO2 is too simplified and not well supported as written. The network captures environmental interconnection well but relies on a weakly justified feedstock generation step.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005"], "suggestions": ["Use hydrothermal formate/methanol/CO intermediates before formaldehyde generation", "Specify the mineral agents and redox sequence more explicitly for hydrothermal carbon reduction"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.88, "rxn_003": 0.35, "rxn_005": 0.58, "rxn_007": 0.93, "rxn_008": 0.84, "rxn_009": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.75, "pathway_coherence": 0.85, "environmental_progression": 0.88, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.81, "feedback": "This route benefits from a literature-consistent formate/formic acid role in facilitating nitrile hydrolysis, which improves alignment with the research findings. The route still inherits the major HCN-source weakness and an overly compressed branched aldehyde synthesis step. Overall, it is one of the better pathways because the hydrolysis logic is chemically coherent.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005"], "suggestions": ["Clarify whether formic acid acts catalytically or stoichiometrically in nitrile hydrolysis", "Anchor HCN production to volcanic lightning literature rather than NH3 + H2 alone"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_004": 0.78, "rxn_005": 0.58, "rxn_006": 0.92, "rxn_007": 0.93, "rxn_008": 0.78, "rxn_009": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.79, "pathway_coherence": 0.86, "environmental_progression": 0.85, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.83, "feedback": "This pathway aligns reasonably well with the literature because it incorporates the Powner-relevant aldehyde chemistry, especially the aldol addition of isobutyraldehyde with formaldehyde to hydroxypivaldehyde. The problem is