mplicated as analogs of biological FeS clusters supporting formate generation under H2-rich vent conditions (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004; He et al., 2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of formaldehyde from reduced C1 feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis with borate-assisted sugar-stabilizing setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, evaporitic or geothermal pool transfer from hydrothermal carbon sources"}, "mechanism": "Reduced C1 species are photochemically transformed to formaldehyde-equivalent carbonyl pools under UV-exposed mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "The deep research report highlights formic acid as a kinetically important facilitator and formaldehyde as a shared carbon extender feeding both Strecker and sugar chemistry; using mineral-assisted photochemical conversion here is a connecting step needed to bridge hydrothermal reduced carbon to surface aldehyde chemistry, and is therefore explicitly speculative but consistent with integrated prebiotic C1 photoredox scenarios (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; reported as a necessary connector beyond direct literature)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface UV cyanosulfidic production and maintenance of hydrogen cyanide pool", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-active sulfide mineral setting with TiO2 photocatalysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV, anoxic volcanic surface environment, cyanosulfidic regime"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry sustains a cyanide reservoir from reduced carbon/nitrogen feedstocks in H2S-rich volcanic settings.", "reasoning": "The literature report emphasizes HCN and H2S as the central feedstocks of the Sutherland-Patel cyanosulfidic network and notes enhancement of branched amino-acid production in sulfur-rich volcanic lightning settings; this node represents the maintained surface HCN reservoir rather than a single clean stoichiometric synthesis event (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formose initiation to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-stabilized formose setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry or evaporitic cycling, UV-exposed surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Self-condensation/rearrangement of formaldehyde under borate-stabilized conditions yields glycolaldehyde as an early C2 aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde is explicitly identified in the report as a key intermediate in prebiotic sugar and cyanosulfidic chemistry, and borate minerals are cited as important stabilizers of reactive sugars and aldehydes in surface settings (Ricardo et al., 2004; Patel et al., 2015; Powner et al., 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation to branched aldehyde precursor pool including isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic setting with sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, neutral to near-neutral pH, iterative homologation chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Iterative UV/H2S-driven homologation of cyanide-derived carbonyl/nitrile intermediates produces higher, including branched, aldehydes that feed Strecker chemistry; isobutyraldehyde is taken as the selected branched aldehyde output.", "reasoning": "The deep research report specifically attributes valine formation in the Sutherland-Patel network to iterative HCN/H2S/UV homologation chemistry and identifies isobutyraldehyde as a validated valine precursor emerging within integrated systems chemistry, while also noting phosphate buffering as important (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Xu et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Powner-type aldol linkage of isobutyraldehyde with formaldehyde within compatible surface networks", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-buffered neutral aqueous medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "network-conditioning step reflecting selective survival/reactivity of isobutyraldehyde in mixed aldehyde pools"}, "mechanism": "Selective aldehyde reactivity in neutral aqueous mixtures preserves and channels isobutyraldehyde-containing streams rather than destroying them, consistent with aldol-active network integration.", "reasoning": "The report highlights Powner-group work showing that isobutyraldehyde selectively participates in compatible aqueous neutral-pH chemistry with formaldehyde to make hydroxypivaldehyde in cofactor-related synthesis; this supports the persistence and network relevance of isobutyraldehyde under mixed prebiotic conditions. This node is intentionally written as a preserving/channeling network step rather than introducing an extra molecule not essential to the valine graph (Liu et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019; as summarized in the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis of valine nitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentration with phosphate-buffered aqueous medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous Strecker conditions in evaporitic or volcanic pools"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with ammonia; cyanide adds to give the alpha-aminonitrile 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "The report identifies the Strecker sequence from isobutyraldehyde to valine nitrile as the primary route in Miller-Urey and meteoritic-type valine synthesis and specifically names 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile as the key precursor (Miller, 1953; Johnson et al., 2008; Cronin & Pizzarello, 1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Partial hydrolysis of valine nitrile to valinamide", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_015", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate/clay-assisted aqueous hydrolysis with formic acid participation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild heating; anoxic; formic acid lowers hydration barrier"}, "mechanism": "Acid-assisted hydration of the nitrile gives the corresponding amide, valinamide, as the first hydrolysis product.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly states that Strecker-derived valine nitrile hydrolyzes first to valine amide and then to valine. It also notes computational evidence that formic acid can substantially lower nitrile hydration barriers relative to water alone, supporting inclusion of formic acid as a kinetically helpful co-reactant (Johnson et al., 2008; Danger et al., 2013; Das et al., 2019 as summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of valinamide to valine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_015", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate/clay-assisted aqueous hydrolysis with formic acid participation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "continued aqueous hydrolysis under anoxic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Further hydration and deamidation convert valinamide to the free amino acid valine.", "reasoning": "Successive hydrolysis from aminonitrile to amide to amino acid is the canonical final portion of Strecker chemistry and is specifically described for valine in the provided report; formic acid is included because the report highlights its barrier-lowering effect in hydration/amination chemistry (Johnson et al., 2008; Cronin & Pizzarello, 1997; Das et al., 2019 as summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrothermal generation/accumulation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from branched aldehyde feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent-surface exchange; proposed reductive carboxylation/oxidation sequence on Fe-S minerals"}, "mechanism": "Branched aldehyde feedstocks imported from surface settings undergo Fe-S-mediated carbonyl/carboxyl transformation to the corresponding alpha-keto acid pool, represented here by alpha-ketoisovalerate.", "reasoning": "The report states that pyruvate-forming reductive carboxylation on greigite/pyrrhotite supports the plausibility of analogous routes to larger C5 keto acids and explicitly notes alpha-ketoisovalerate as the direct hydrothermal precursor to valine. This step remains partially speculative because the exact upstream synthesis of alpha-ketoisovalerate is identified in the report as an open bottleneck, but its inclusion is necessary to connect the literature-supported hydrothermal valine-forming step to the rest of the network (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2017; Kaur et al., 2023 as summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353-373K (optimized at 353K/80C)", "pressure": "5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni0 with Fe-S mineral support represented by greigite; Fe0 as reductant", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-11, optimized near pH 11, 72 h, serpentinizing vent conditions, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoisovalerate undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by hydrogenation/reductive amination to valine under Ni/H2 and alkaline vent conditions.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest direct literature-supported valine synthesis step in the report: nickel-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate at 80C, pH 11, 5 bar H2 gives valine in high yield under vent-like conditions; Fe-S minerals are also discussed as plausible hydrothermal catalytic partners in related prebiotic aminations (Kaur et al., 2023; Muchowska et al., 2019; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic condensation of valine to valylvaline", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null", "null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "333-363K (up to 363K/90C)", "pressure": "ambient to elevated", "catalyst": "manganese oxides or mineral interfaces in prebiotic pools", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling or geothermal heating; peptide formation favored over days"}, "mechanism": "Concentrated valine undergoes dehydration condensation on mineral interfaces to form short peptides, represented by the dipeptide valylvaline.", "reasoning": "The report notes manganese oxides as efficient catalysts for amino-acid polymerization, with peptide yields peaking around 90C over extended times. Although direct valine polymerization is less studied than glycine/alanine and may suffer steric hindrance, extending the same principle to valine is reasonable for biochemical capture of the amino acid pool (Rode et al., 1999; Commeyras et al., 2004; Bujdak et al., 1995 as summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical hydrolytic release of valine from primitive peptides", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null", "null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "none required", "aqueous": "true", "other": "re-entry of peptide-bound valine into pool chemistry during hydration phases"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis of primitive valine-containing peptides replenishes free valine in fluctuating wet-dry environments.", "reasoning": "The report frames peptide formation in the context of the water paradox and environmental cycling; hydrolysis during rehydration is an unavoidable complementary process that closes the pool-maintenance cycle and connects monomer synthesis to transient peptide capture (Forsythe et al., 2015; Rode et al., 1999; explicitly used here as a necessary systems-chemistry connector)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon to surface Strecker valine", "description": "Reduced carbon from hydrothermal CO2 fixation is transferred to surface aldehyde chemistry, producing isobutyraldehyde and then valine via the canonical Strecker nitrile-amide-acid sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "S