lly supported from Miller-Urey to meteoritic and laboratory Strecker contexts, and the pathway is internally coherent.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add explicit pH and hydrolysis conditions to distinguish nitrile-to-amide and amide-to-acid rates.\",\n        \"If desired, include atmospheric or meteoritic provenance of isobutyraldehyde/HCN pools for even stronger environmental grounding.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.48,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.22,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.34,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.38,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.56,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.68,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.87,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.68,\n      \"feedback\": \"The terminal hydrothermal step from alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine is excellently aligned with the literature, especially Ni/H2/alkaline vent chemistry. The problem is upstream: the production of alpha-ketoisovalerate from isobutyraldehyde and CO2 is not well specified and is much more speculative than the network suggests. As a result, the pathway reaches a well-supported endpoint through a poorly justified precursor synthesis.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Introduce a more credible route to alpha-ketoisovalerate, potentially through branched thioester/carboxylation chemistry or explicit analogs of pyruvate-forming FeS chemistry.\",\n        \"Use the literature-supported hydrothermal conditions for rxn_011 explicitly: about 80C, pH 11, around 5 bar H2, Ni or Fe-S catalysts.\",\n        \"Do not collapse multiple carbon-skeleton building steps into a single carboxylation reaction.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.34,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.38,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.56,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.7,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.69,\n      \"feedback\": \"This shortcut effectively demonstrates cross-environment transfer from a surface aldehyde pool into hydrothermal amino acid synthesis, which is a strong systems-chemistry concept. Yet both the formation of isobutyraldehyde and its conversion to alpha-ketoisovalerate remain underspecified. The final reductive amination step is highly credible.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Make the surface aldehyde generation more explicit and experimentally anchored.\",\n        \"Add intermediates between isobutyraldehyde and alpha-ketoisovalerate, such as cyanohydrin or alpha-hydroxy acid/keto acid interconversion.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.73,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.96,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"As a standalone imported-precursor pathway, this is strongly supported by the hydrothermal literature. Reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine under Ni/Fe-S/H2 alkaline conditions is one of the best-supported routes in the entire network and matches the research summary very well.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify whether alpha-ketoisovalerate is assumed to be delivered from surface chemistry or